Rym: We've talked about server rooms.

648
00:40:40,276 --> 00:40:41,300
Rym: We've talked about HVAC.

649
00:40:41,862 --> 00:40:43,449
Rym: Never talked about refrigeration.

650
00:40:45,093 --> 00:40:47,168
Rym: Like as a technology, arguably.

651
00:40:47,631 --> 00:40:52,041
Scott: I mean, we don't need to explain how refrigeration works with compressors and whatnot.

652
00:40:52,101 --> 00:40:52,282
Scott: Right.

653
00:40:52,322 --> 00:40:55,630
Scott: You can look that up on YouTube and find better visualizations of it.

654
00:40:55,790 --> 00:41:00,490
Scott: I think even Rym's favorite technology guy, whatever, has a video or two on it also.

655
00:41:01,050 --> 00:41:05,290
Rym: Suffice it to say, the only thing you need to know if you don't know is that all refrigeration is a concept.

656
00:41:06,071 --> 00:41:07,935
Rym: It does one of two things and that's it.

657
00:41:07,995 --> 00:41:15,090
Rym: It either removes heat from an environment into a medium in some fashion, like, say, dry ice in a room.

658
00:41:15,471 --> 00:41:25,110
Rym: It's pulling heat into something to cool the space or it is actively pumping heat out of a space into the broader environment.

659
00:41:25,530 --> 00:41:26,394
Rym: It's just a heat pump.

660
00:41:26,755 --> 00:41:27,719
Rym: You Google for heat pump.

661
00:41:28,061 --> 00:41:30,210
Rym: There are plenty of people, like Scott said, who will explain it to you.

662
00:41:30,870 --> 00:41:32,254
Scott: So there's many different methods.

663
00:41:32,395 --> 00:41:37,590
Scott: There's many different methods of doing this that vary sometimes in big ways, sometimes in small ways.

664
00:41:37,890 --> 00:41:40,669
Scott: But, you know, regardless, like that's what you're doing.

665
00:41:41,451 --> 00:41:52,850
Rym: Less than 200 years ago, the primary way a lot of people in America got things like ice was harvesting it from rivers in the winter and storing it under, like, bales of hay.

666
00:41:54,332 --> 00:41:54,514
Scott: Yup.

667
00:41:54,554 --> 00:41:56,169
Scott: I didn't even know where the hell they got dry ice.

668
00:41:59,371 --> 00:42:03,101
Rym: I'm trying to think about, I know about methods from the 1900s to make dry ice.

669
00:42:03,201 --> 00:42:06,770
Rym: I don't know if and how dry ice might have been made before that, actually.

670
00:42:07,152 --> 00:42:10,209
Rym: I don't know the history of dry ice at all, I realize, other than that one thing.

671
00:42:10,289 --> 00:42:10,470
Rym: Anyway.

672
00:42:11,670 --> 00:42:22,730
Scott: I do remember, though, my grandfather talking about how back in the day, it's like you look at today and people drive food around and other things that need to be cold in refrigerated trucks.

673
00:42:22,870 --> 00:42:31,370
Scott: Just a big truck that has a refrigerator attached to it and the inside of the truck is cold and now you can drive meat around town in the summer.

674
00:42:31,550 --> 00:42:31,711
Scott: Right.

675
00:42:32,232 --> 00:42:40,690
Scott: But he said back in the day, all they would do is just have a truck and throw a piece of dry ice in the truck and maybe put a fan near it.

676
00:42:41,832 --> 00:42:42,476
Scott: And that was it.

677
00:42:42,597 --> 00:42:44,568
Scott: And the truck would be cold as hell.

678
00:42:45,251 --> 00:42:45,531
Rym: Yup.

679
00:42:46,013 --> 00:42:46,474
Rym: All right.

680
00:42:46,495 --> 00:42:46,735
Rym: Yes.

681
00:42:46,816 --> 00:42:50,407
Rym: Dry ice was observed and documented in detail in the 1830s.

682
00:42:52,391 --> 00:42:59,430
Rym: And it looks like in the early 1900s is when manufacturing processes that are not that different from what we do today were invented.

683
00:43:00,214 --> 00:43:02,930
Scott: And Rym has read Wikipedia to you as a service.

684
00:43:03,470 --> 00:43:04,533
Rym: Yup, because I was curious.

685
00:43:04,814 --> 00:43:10,690
Rym: I did not know if they were able to make dry ice in the late 1800s and the answer seems to be sort of.

686
00:43:11,770 --> 00:43:12,111
Scott: Okay.

687
00:43:13,052 --> 00:43:29,050
Scott: Regardless, all the ways of keeping things cold back in the day, meaning up until relatively recently in terms of human history, was get cold shit and put it near the shit that needs to be cold until it runs out and then get more cold shit.

688
00:43:29,231 --> 00:43:30,735
Scott: Even in the 20th century, right?

689
00:43:30,755 --> 00:43:32,019
Scott: You had the icebox, right?

690
00:43:32,039 --> 00:43:33,383
Scott: They didn't have refrigerators in houses.

691
00:43:33,583 --> 00:43:35,910
Scott: You would have someone deliver fucking ice to your house.

692
00:43:36,470 --> 00:43:39,899
Scott: You'd put the ice into the bottom of the fridge, right?

693
00:43:40,140 --> 00:43:43,750
Scott: The fridge would be cold until the ice melted and then they would deliver more ice.

694
00:43:43,910 --> 00:43:46,849
Scott: And that's how you kept food in your house from spoiling.

695
00:43:47,610 --> 00:43:58,868
Rym: So, my grandparents had, when I was a kid, I might have talked about this on GeekNights more than a decade ago, they had a general electric refrigerator from the late 1940s.

696
00:44:00,710 --> 00:44:01,856
Rym: And it wasn't their primary fridge.

697
00:44:01,896 --> 00:44:04,288
Rym: They had a more recent fridge in the main house.

698
00:44:05,290 --> 00:44:11,264
Rym: But in the furnace room, they had that old late 40s fridge and it still worked.

699
00:44:11,625 --> 00:44:13,610
Rym: And they were still using it because they thought it was neat.

700
00:44:13,951 --> 00:44:16,578
Rym: It never had any maintenance other than some lubrication at any point.

701
00:44:17,200 --> 00:44:18,905
Rym: And as a kid, I was vaguely obsessed with it.

702
00:44:19,185 --> 00:44:20,830
Rym: And all they stored in there was soda pop.

703
00:44:22,411 --> 00:44:25,569
Rym: It had this really cool chunky latching mechanism to open it.

704
00:44:26,490 --> 00:44:27,749
Scott: Yep, that's how they do.

705
00:44:28,030 --> 00:44:29,654
Rym: Yep, and you had to manually defrost it.

706
00:44:29,734 --> 00:44:35,770
Rym: But yeah, so early refrigerators that plugged into an outlet and used electricity, like my grandparents...

707
00:44:35,850 --> 00:44:38,896
Scott: Hold on, there's one thing for the ice boxes, right?

708
00:44:38,916 --> 00:44:45,430
Scott: There's one thing about the ice box that I never knew and still don't know, but I only have a guess.

709
00:44:45,850 --> 00:44:48,844
Scott: Which is that, you know, the ice cube would melt, the big ice cube, right?

710
00:44:49,125 --> 00:44:50,010
Scott: Then they'd bring a new one.

711
00:44:51,310 --> 00:44:53,416
Scott: Did you just drain the water down the drain?

712
00:44:54,098 --> 00:44:55,121
Scott: Or drink the water?

713
00:44:55,663 --> 00:44:57,448
Scott: Because the old ice cube melted into water.

714
00:44:57,468 --> 00:44:58,090
Scott: It didn't disappear.

715
00:44:59,650 --> 00:45:00,173
Scott: What did they do?

716
00:45:00,193 --> 00:45:00,997
Scott: Did they pump it out?

717
00:45:01,641 --> 00:45:03,310
Scott: What did they do with the water from the old ice cube?

718
00:45:04,072 --> 00:45:12,650
Rym: So the Wikipedia page doesn't actually say much about it, except it talks a lot about how all nice ice chests had spigots to drain it and catch pans and holding tanks.

719
00:45:13,510 --> 00:45:15,850
Scott: Okay, so you would drain it and it would go down the drain into the sewer?

720
00:45:16,430 --> 00:45:17,379
Rym: Yeah, pretty much.

721
00:45:17,621 --> 00:45:18,489
Rym: I doubt people...

722
00:45:18,590 --> 00:45:19,690
Scott: Like down the sink, basically?

723
00:45:20,291 --> 00:45:22,008
Rym: Unless you lived somewhere where... That was my guess.

724
00:45:22,651 --> 00:45:30,190
Rym: If you lived somewhere where you didn't have running water in your house, which, frankly, in the early 1900s in the US, not that uncommon.

725
00:45:30,773 --> 00:45:34,750
Scott: But if you lived in a place without running water, are you really going to be in range of an ice delivery man?

726
00:45:35,370 --> 00:45:35,631
Rym: Might have.

727
00:45:36,013 --> 00:45:36,474
Rym: Small town.

728
00:45:36,976 --> 00:45:40,129
Rym: A lot of houses in the 20s did not have...

729
00:45:40,390 --> 00:45:44,870
Scott: Since it's just water, it is safe to just drain it out into the backyard or some shit, right?

730
00:45:44,910 --> 00:45:44,996
Scott: Yeah.

731
00:45:45,810 --> 00:45:47,570
Scott: As long as you don't drain it on your kitchen floor.

732
00:45:47,830 --> 00:45:54,388
Rym: But we had a beefy dehumidifier in the basement when I was a kid, and we would actually take that water and use it to water the plants in the house.

733
00:45:54,468 --> 00:45:55,090
Rym: Just, why not?

734
00:45:55,992 --> 00:45:56,609
Scott: Yeah, why not?

735
00:45:57,211 --> 00:45:58,272
Rym: But yeah, refrigeration.

736
00:45:58,412 --> 00:46:16,430
Rym: I talk about this a lot on GeekNights, but in general, one of the most important things you can do if you care about technology is not to just focus on the bleeding edge of the cool new stuff we can do, but to think about technology that works and how it can be distributed more equitably, used more efficiently, etc.

737
00:46:17,630 --> 00:46:21,530
Rym: Refrigeration is one of the most important things humans have ever invented.

738
00:46:22,111 --> 00:46:25,660
Scott: Yeah, if you play Civilization, it gets a whole spot on the tech tree.

739
00:46:25,720 --> 00:46:30,010
Scott: I think in every Civilization game that I'm aware of, refrigeration has its own item.

740
00:46:30,451 --> 00:46:32,185
Rym: It's like, "Oh yeah, double food from all your shit

741
00:46:32,226 --> 00:46:32,407
Rym: now!".

742
00:46:33,433 --> 00:46:33,970
Scott: Yup, exactly.

743
00:46:33,970 --> 00:46:35,499
Rym: Your cities can just grow like crazy.

744
00:46:36,163 --> 00:46:37,230
Rym: See, also, sewers.

745
00:46:38,370 --> 00:46:38,541
Scott: Yup.

746
00:46:39,451 --> 00:46:39,836
Rym: Hospitals.

747
00:46:39,856 --> 00:46:41,010
Rym: that comes after hospitals.

748
00:46:43,276 --> 00:46:48,570
Scott: After plumbing, I think refrigeration is the next most important invention for human society.

749
00:46:48,910 --> 00:46:49,051
Rym: Yup.

750
00:46:49,494 --> 00:46:50,724
Rym: I mean, it's to the point to where...

751
00:46:51,530 --> 00:46:55,288
Scott: It's dependent on electricity, which at least kind of, right?

752
00:46:55,348 --> 00:46:55,690
Scott: Mostly.

753
00:46:56,230 --> 00:46:59,329
Scott: There are plenty... So I guess you could rank electricity higher, kind of.

754
00:46:59,550 --> 00:47:09,210
Rym: But there are plenty of cooling mechanisms that are as effective as modern day refrigeration that uses electricity that do not require electricity.

755
00:47:09,370 --> 00:47:09,990
Rym: There's lots of ways to do it.

756
00:47:10,010 --> 00:47:15,170
Scott: That is true, but the vast majority of refrigeration around the world is the electric kind.

757
00:47:15,410 --> 00:47:15,751
Scott: Yup.

758
00:47:16,192 --> 00:47:23,310
Rym: But I think the most important thing about it is just that it allowed perishable food to be stored with relative safety.

759
00:47:24,364 --> 00:47:24,509
Scott: Yup.

760
00:47:24,890 --> 00:47:26,013
Rym: Like, beyond everything else.

761
00:47:26,554 --> 00:47:42,030
Rym: Because even in a modern world, in the year 2022, where I have a refrigerator and a freezer, I still have to put a not insignificant amount of mental effort into thinking about the safety of various foods and what should be stored where.

762
00:47:42,170 --> 00:47:43,735
Rym: And can this be frozen?

763
00:47:43,795 --> 00:47:44,939
Rym: Can this be refrigerated?

764
00:47:45,019 --> 00:47:46,122
Rym: Should this be refrigerated?

765
00:47:46,443 --> 00:47:48,830
Rym: Some foods shouldn't be refrigerated, like tomatoes!

766
00:47:50,070 --> 00:47:50,973
Scott: But I mean, think about this.

767
00:47:51,053 --> 00:47:53,179
Scott: Back in the day, before refrigeration, right?

768
00:47:53,259 --> 00:47:56,328
Scott: It's like, okay, you either had to get everything fresh, or, right?

769
00:47:57,411 --> 00:48:05,778
Scott: You store some food, okay, well then what if, you know, you might have to like... I mean, any food you want to store, you don't have to do some sort of preservation work, right?

770
00:48:05,839 --> 00:48:12,310
Scott: Like, you know, maybe can it, or, you know, what's it called?

771
00:48:12,650 --> 00:48:16,890
Scott: Like, you know, you can't just save the beef for tomorrow, you gotta make some beef jerky instead, right?

772
00:48:17,030 --> 00:48:18,107
Scott: It's like, you know, stuff like that.

773
00:48:19,910 --> 00:48:21,477
Rym: Like, leftovers were difficult.

774
00:48:21,638 --> 00:48:24,150
Rym: Leftovers like we know them today are basically impossible without refrigeration.

775
00:48:24,290 --> 00:48:29,200
Scott: Right, it's like, okay, then you get, it's like, okay, you have this sort of battle going on.

776
00:48:29,261 --> 00:48:30,724
Scott: It's like, do I save food?

777
00:48:30,744 --> 00:48:33,790
Scott: Do I eat food, more food than I can stomach?

778
00:48:34,250 --> 00:48:35,393
Scott: Do I go hungry?

779
00:48:35,413 --> 00:48:41,126
Scott: You know, do I eat, do I, the food's older, but do I eat it anyway and risk getting sick?

780
00:48:41,226 --> 00:48:43,050
Scott: Do I even know that the food will make me sick?

781
00:48:43,972 --> 00:48:45,409
Scott: Just have warm meat lying around.

782
00:48:45,890 --> 00:49:02,570
Rym: Yup, and while there are a bunch of adjacent technologies that have achieved similar results, like to keep things cool, like evaporative coolers, like those have existed since ancient times, they are much less reliable, and they're not as controllable.

783
00:49:02,690 --> 00:49:08,770
Rym: The big thing about the refrigeration we're talking about, like a modern fridge, is that you pick a temperature, and it is at that temperature.

784
00:49:10,510 --> 00:49:17,610
Scott: Also, you know, you talk about, you know, food traveling, right, so it's like you'd have to eat food that came from somewhere close.

785
00:49:17,770 --> 00:49:28,150
Scott: You couldn't eat a food that, you know, wouldn't, a spoilable food, that came from far away, you know, like, you get a fruit from another country, it's like you couldn't have that.

786
00:49:28,370 --> 00:49:31,798
Scott: It would be disgusting by the time it took a boat over, or even if it took a plane.

787
00:49:31,858 --> 00:49:37,110
Scott: somehow, you know, I guess planes and refrigerators were invented around, you know.

788
00:49:38,531 --> 00:49:43,270
Scott: But, you know, it's like before the, you know, you'd have to take a boat, and it's like it would be rotten.

789
00:49:43,790 --> 00:49:50,590
Scott: It's like you would never be able to eat that unless you went to the other place, then you could eat the food from there, but you couldn't have brought the food from home, right?

790
00:49:50,610 --> 00:49:53,070
Scott: It would be disgusting by the time you got to the other side, right?

791
00:49:54,410 --> 00:50:05,250
Scott: It's like, you know, on boats, it's like the navies would be bringing around live animals on the boat, because otherwise, it's like if you just had all the animals pre-butchered, it's like guess what, you're not going to make it across the ocean.

792
00:50:05,671 --> 00:50:05,972
Rym: Yup.

793
00:50:06,092 --> 00:50:12,209
Rym: Similarly, most of the food they brought was all the food you imagine on a Napoleonic era ship.

794
00:50:13,691 --> 00:50:14,114
Rym: Weevils.

795
00:50:14,234 --> 00:50:16,389
Rym: Weevils and hard bread and salt pork.

796
00:50:17,870 --> 00:50:18,391
Scott: Exactly.

797
00:50:18,471 --> 00:50:21,376
Scott: So, yeah, refrigeration was huge.

798
00:50:22,158 --> 00:50:29,210
Scott: So, modern day, right, you go and you probably just buy a fucking refrigerator, but there's so many different ones now.

799
00:50:29,651 --> 00:50:37,310
Scott: When I was a kid, everyone I knew just had the standard refrigerator, which was just freezer on top, fridge on the bottom.

800
00:50:37,950 --> 00:50:40,414
Rym: When I was a kid, there were exactly two kinds of fridges.

801
00:50:40,815 --> 00:50:49,790
Rym: Everyone, with a handful of exceptions, had what you describe, and there were a handful of kids whose parents were rich, who lived in the nicer houses and the newer developments in the suburbs.

802
00:50:50,311 --> 00:51:00,090
Rym: They had the early versions of those modern fancy refrigerators with a bunch of features on them, like an ice thing and a water thing in the front, and the doors that opened to the sides.

803
00:51:00,230 --> 00:51:04,003
Scott: I feel like I didn't see any of those until the mid to late 90s.

804
00:51:04,023 --> 00:51:06,090
Scott: They probably existed earlier, but I didn't see any.

805
00:51:06,170 --> 00:51:14,990
Rym: I saw them in the houses of a handful of kids I knew in middle school, who were way richer than us and lived in way nicer suburbs than we did.

806
00:51:14,990 --> 00:51:20,990
Scott: What I did see were people who had, you know, larger houses, they had garages and large basements.

807
00:51:21,230 --> 00:51:29,950
Rym: Oh, we had a beverage fridge, we had a fridge in the kitchen, and we had a, basically, when we bought that new fridge, the old fridge wasn't that broken, it was just like old and inefficient.

808
00:51:30,350 --> 00:51:32,470
Rym: We stuck it in the garage, and that became the soda fridge.

809
00:51:32,810 --> 00:51:39,570
Scott: Yeah, we might have done that if we had had such a space, right, in our house, but we also didn't drink soda, so it wasn't really a thing.

810
00:51:40,371 --> 00:51:42,090
Scott: But people had chest freezers.

811
00:51:42,695 --> 00:51:44,510
Rym: We also had a chest freezer.

812
00:51:45,750 --> 00:51:58,950
Scott: Yeah, so the people with the chest freezers, for example, right, I remember you'd buy your turkey on Thanksgiving, and you'd go to the person's house who had the chest freezer, and leave it in there until Thanksgiving.

813
00:51:59,190 --> 00:52:01,110
Scott: Then you would go there the day before Thanksgiving.

814
00:52:01,150 --> 00:52:03,550
Rym: If I had enough space for it, I would 100% have a chest freezer today.

815
00:52:03,610 --> 00:52:05,850
Scott: Because we didn't have room in our regular fridge to store a whole fucking turkey.

816
00:52:06,190 --> 00:52:09,690
Rym: I would absolutely have a chest freezer if there was anywhere to put it in this apartment.

817
00:52:11,002 --> 00:52:11,169
Scott: Yeah.

818
00:52:13,110 --> 00:52:26,450
Rym: There's also those cool, there are the Peltier, like there's chest freezers and chest refrigerators that are designed for long-term storage to be energy efficient, and they tend to have a really weak-sauce Peltier device instead of the more traditional cooling.

819
00:52:26,951 --> 00:52:33,350
Rym: And they basically take a long time to get cold, but if you don't open often, they just stay cold using almost no electricity.

820
00:52:34,071 --> 00:52:40,630
Scott: I mean, the best memory I had of chest freezers was the people across the street had one in the garage, and that's where they put the popsicles.

821
00:52:40,850 --> 00:52:43,057
Scott: It was like, you didn't have to go in their house to go and get a popsicle.

822
00:52:43,077 --> 00:52:45,124
Scott: You could just be like, "Bam, you're already outside having a good

823
00:52:45,144 --> 00:52:45,405
Scott: time.".

824
00:52:45,445 --> 00:52:46,770
Scott: Just like, boom, popsicle right there.

825
00:52:47,070 --> 00:52:55,730
Rym: I remember going into random friends' parents' garages and just taking ice cream and popsicles out of their chest freezer, probably without permission, because the kids would all just kind of do this.

826
00:52:57,410 --> 00:53:00,950
Scott: It was equal opportunity, except for our house, because ours were in the freezer.

827
00:53:04,131 --> 00:53:14,130
Rym: Though, what I do, the thing that always did bother me is every fridge I've ever seen that has an external port for water and ice, that shit never works.

828
00:53:14,990 --> 00:53:18,740
Scott: Okay, well, first of all, it works sometimes, right?

829
00:53:19,141 --> 00:53:22,810
Scott: The thing that bothers me is, A, inconsistent design.

830
00:53:23,251 --> 00:53:28,960
Scott: A lot of times, I try to use it, and the design of what I'm supposed to do is not obvious.

831
00:53:29,001 --> 00:53:34,330
Scott: Some of them, there's the plastic thing, you push your cup into it, and it's like, "Ah, that should make water come

832
00:53:34,410 --> 00:53:34,490
Scott: out.".

833
00:53:34,570 --> 00:53:37,538
Scott: And some of them, that makes the ice come out, and some of them makes the water come out.

834
00:53:37,578 --> 00:53:38,561
Scott: Some of them don't even have that.

835
00:53:39,022 --> 00:53:41,890
Scott: Some of them, you gotta push buttons on the face of the thing to make stuff happen.

836
00:53:41,890 --> 00:53:47,670
Rym: A lot of times, they have a dial and a switch, and you set it to what you want to happen when the plastic thing gets hit.

837
00:53:48,151 --> 00:53:49,936
Scott: And there should only ever be two buttons.

838
00:53:50,257 --> 00:53:51,781
Scott: Spit out water and spit out ice.

839
00:53:51,821 --> 00:53:53,004
Scott: Some of these things have more buttons.

840
00:53:53,044 --> 00:53:54,327
Scott: What the fuck are those buttons for?

841
00:53:54,548 --> 00:53:55,390
Scott: Like, seriously?

842
00:53:55,970 --> 00:54:00,190
Rym: Crushed ice versus chopped ice, even though they end up being kind of the same on most of these things.

843
00:54:00,570 --> 00:54:01,572
Scott: Yeah, I don't give a shit.

844
00:54:01,592 --> 00:54:03,675
Scott: If you give a shit about that, you got problems, right?

845
00:54:03,715 --> 00:54:13,090
Scott: And then, the other thing is, I guess if you're extra fancy, I imagine, I've never seen one, there must be one out there that will carbonate the water, right?

846
00:54:14,211 --> 00:54:21,090
