00:55:06,888 --> 00:55:07,650
Scott: Things of that nature.

856
00:55:08,251 --> 00:55:19,850
Scott: If we had the spigot on the front of the fridge, right, then I could save a lot of space in the fridge by not having all this water, like, saved up and all the time.

857
00:55:20,391 --> 00:55:23,830
Scott: It's like, yeah, I could drink from the tap, but the point is to make it cold first.

858
00:55:24,931 --> 00:55:28,970
Rym: At least our tap is shockingly cold, even in the dead of summer, for some reason.

859
00:55:29,110 --> 00:55:30,054
Rym: Sometimes, sometimes.

860
00:55:30,074 --> 00:55:33,630
Scott: But it is a useful feature to have for space savings, right?

861
00:55:35,130 --> 00:55:40,429
Scott: The ice that goes right into the glass, eh, okay, me, eh, you know.

862
00:55:40,710 --> 00:55:50,290
Rym: I just find that most of the times, when I try to use one of those things at someone else's house, or, like, in an Airbnb, or anywhere that I encounter one, they fail in some way.

863
00:55:50,610 --> 00:55:56,368
Rym: Even the last time I visited my brother, I go to use the ice maker, and suddenly he's like, "Ah, the ice maker doesn't really work, don't do it, don't touch

864
00:55:56,428 --> 00:55:56,468
Rym: it!".

865
00:55:57,276 --> 00:55:57,487
Scott: Yep.

866
00:55:57,871 --> 00:55:59,789
Rym: I just feel like they're cheap and they tend to break.

867
00:56:00,611 --> 00:56:05,630
Scott: Our fridge has the kind of ice maker I like, which is the one where you can turn it on and off.

868
00:56:05,890 --> 00:56:09,910
Scott: Right now it's on, because I just used a bunch of ice, but I turn it off soon once the bucket fills up.

869
00:56:10,050 --> 00:56:17,430
Scott: But basically, there's a bucket in the freezer, and you just turn it on, and you wait, and eventually the freezer bucket is full of ice, just tons of ice.

870
00:56:18,891 --> 00:56:26,950
Scott: And I like this because, A, you know, ice cube trays, I used to use those, and it's like you had to fill them, carry them to the freezer full of water.

871
00:56:27,711 --> 00:56:37,130
Scott: You can't really have that many trays in the freezer because there's not enough room, and you don't have that much ice, and then it sublimates if you don't use it quickly enough, and then you don't have ice when you want it.

872
00:56:37,550 --> 00:56:43,309
Scott: The bucket full of ice in the freezer is just like, "Yep, there's just a fucking bucket full of ice, you can go wild with the

873
00:56:43,470 --> 00:56:43,570
Scott: ice.".

874
00:56:43,650 --> 00:56:49,090
Scott: It's like, oh, you want to, you know, you can put a couple cubes in a glass, you're like, just dip your glass in there like you're scooping.

875
00:56:49,610 --> 00:56:51,256
Scott: You just scoop it all the way full, right?

876
00:56:51,276 --> 00:56:54,830
Scott: Take a water bottle, just jam it with ice all the way to the top.

877
00:56:54,930 --> 00:56:59,190
Scott: You don't get to give a shit, you get so much ice, and you don't have to, you know, you don't have to work.

878
00:56:59,770 --> 00:57:06,150
Scott: You don't have to like, you know, remember to manage the ice, or to make cubes, or to fill anything, it's just, it's always there.

879
00:57:06,530 --> 00:57:12,910
Scott: And if it ever runs low, you push the button until it's full again, and then when it's done, you push the button one more time.

880
00:57:13,090 --> 00:57:18,059
Rym: Now for whatever reason, I don't use ice, like, I almost never use ice in my day-to-day life.

881
00:57:25,251 --> 00:57:30,870
Rym: So all I have is one little silicone tray that makes four giant ice cubes with a cover on it so they don't sublimate.

882
00:57:32,992 --> 00:57:36,750
Rym: And anytime I use two of them, I put some water in there, so I always have ice cubes.

883
00:57:37,390 --> 00:57:40,590
Scott: I mean, this time of year, you know, I'm filling coolers, I'm filling water bottles.

884
00:57:40,870 --> 00:57:41,272
Scott: Coolers!

885
00:57:41,454 --> 00:57:44,110
Rym: I just go to the bodega and buy a bag of ice for a dollar.

886
00:57:44,230 --> 00:57:46,889
Scott: That costs money, and you gotta carry the ice, and...

887
00:57:47,050 --> 00:57:47,687
Rym: Bodega's right there!

888
00:57:49,113 --> 00:57:50,190
Scott: It's still, it's work, right?

889
00:57:50,250 --> 00:57:53,110
Rym: Also, our freezer's usually pretty much full of food.

890
00:57:54,751 --> 00:57:56,118
Scott: Yeah, ours is not that full of food.

891
00:57:56,178 --> 00:57:57,284
Scott: There's only two people living here.

892
00:57:57,304 --> 00:57:58,450
Scott: Why would you have that much food in there?

893
00:57:58,550 --> 00:57:59,607
Rym: Well, we keep a lot of stuff in there.

894
00:58:00,810 --> 00:58:01,040
Scott: Eat it!

895
00:58:01,770 --> 00:58:02,590
Rym: Yeah, then we kill it with more!

896
00:58:07,732 --> 00:58:10,790
Rym: But living in an apartment is a little annoying because there are better fridges.

897
00:58:10,990 --> 00:58:15,390
Rym: Like, I get a much better fridge than what we have, but I don't own this place, the building owns the fridge.

898
00:58:15,450 --> 00:58:18,630
Scott: Yeah, when you rent, you don't have a choice of fridge, so I've never bought a fridge in my life.

899
00:58:18,994 --> 00:58:20,208
Rym: Yup, as much as I would want to.

900
00:58:21,450 --> 00:58:25,230
Rym: And, what's funny is a lot of people, even now, I see our friends still debating fridges.

901
00:58:26,090 --> 00:58:38,430
Rym: A lot of people have a lot of shocking misconceptions about, like, how different configurations of fridges being more or less efficient, and it's almost all aesthetics and style, and very little of it affects the efficiency.

902
00:58:38,710 --> 00:58:45,010
Rym: But, from what I do know, a handful of things that people would think would be more efficient end up being way less efficient.

903
00:58:45,090 --> 00:58:51,130
Rym: Like, case in point, the drawer freezer, those things just jettison cold air compared to a regular one.

904
00:58:52,090 --> 00:58:59,690
Scott: Yeah, I mean, well, people, I don't know how many people realize that, like, you know, you have a fridge, the cooling is all happening in the freezer, right?

905
00:58:59,790 --> 00:59:10,210
Scott: The fridge, part of your refrigerator, is actually just getting, sort of, you know, the cool air left over from the freezer, sort of goes into the fridge by, like, a vent, and that's what makes the fridge cold.

906
00:59:10,851 --> 00:59:13,910
Scott: All the actual active cooling is happening in the freezer zone.

907
00:59:14,070 --> 00:59:24,990
Scott: So, the classic style with the freezer on top, you know, cold air goes down, warm air goes up, is much more efficient than the freezer on bottom kind, right?

908
00:59:25,090 --> 00:59:29,590
Scott: Because the cold air from the freezer just naturally goes down into the fridge on its own.

909
00:59:30,330 --> 00:59:33,990
Scott: If you had to make the cold air go up, well, now, you know, it's not so simple, right?

910
00:59:33,990 --> 00:59:35,909
Scott: You might have to have a little fan in there, who knows?

911
00:59:36,431 --> 00:59:52,230
Rym: Now, I will admit, if I owned a place and I were rich, I would be really interested in one of those integrated refrigeration systems, where you don't have just one big fridge, you just have some of your cupboards are just refrigerated to different temperatures.

912
00:59:53,270 --> 00:59:53,711
Scott: Mm-hmm.

913
00:59:53,731 --> 01:00:05,467
Scott: I mean, as inefficient and wasteful as that is, the convenience and amazingness of, like, you know, "Hey, next to your cabinet full of glasses is a refrigerated cabinet full of

914
01:00:05,528 --> 01:00:05,989
Scott: beverages.".

915
01:00:06,370 --> 01:00:13,670
Scott: And then, you know, next to where the cutting board is, right, in your work area, well, that's where the vegetable fridge is, right?

916
01:00:13,730 --> 01:00:24,910
Rym: But also, depending, that could be more efficient if done in a nuanced way around things, like, not everything needs to be cooled to the temperature of a refrigerator.

917
01:00:24,990 --> 01:00:29,450
Rym: Then we pick that temperature because that is safe for pretty much anything for a short amount of time.

918
01:00:30,211 --> 01:00:32,750
Rym: Like, that is a food safety temperature we've chosen.

919
01:00:33,010 --> 01:00:38,650
Rym: But, like, a lot of vegetables, they'll keep on Humidity also could be customized per fridge, yeah.

920
01:00:38,730 --> 01:00:42,223
Rym: If they're justthey just need to be kept at a consistent temperature.

921
01:00:42,264 --> 01:00:53,370
Rym: that's slightly lower than room temperature, so a really weak-sauce Peltier system for the vegetable crisper could mean you don't have to waste all this energy cooling all your lettuces to 40 degrees Fahrenheit.

922
01:00:53,491 --> 01:00:56,310
Rym: Like, you could haveyou could actually probably save energy.

923
01:00:56,910 --> 01:01:00,710
Rym: But, it's hard to calculate that because those are bespoke systems.

924
01:01:00,870 --> 01:01:02,249
Rym: Like, that's not something you just go and buy.

925
01:01:02,631 --> 01:01:04,550
Rym: That's something a rich person gets installed into their house.

926
01:01:05,991 --> 01:01:10,990
Scott: Yeah, I mean, well, I mean, there are non-rich people who do have multiple fridges for other reasons, right?

927
01:01:11,090 --> 01:01:16,670
Scott: Most notably, people who keep kosher, and they gotta separate their meat fridge from their dairy fridge.

928
01:01:16,870 --> 01:01:17,152
Scott: Yup.

929
01:01:17,634 --> 01:01:20,390
Rym: I used to have because it was a gift, and it was actually really useful.

930
01:01:20,390 --> 01:01:29,066
Rym: I had a wine fridge thatall it did was chill wine, but ityou know, wine doesn't need to get that cold, so it saved energy because it just kept the wine at the temperature.

931
01:01:29,087 --> 01:01:29,649
Rym: you would drink it.

932
01:01:30,070 --> 01:01:36,090
Rym: You type a number in, it just keeps itbut when that broke, I did not replace it because now I live in a tiny apartment.

933
01:01:36,990 --> 01:01:37,192
Scott: Yup.

934
01:01:38,925 --> 01:01:39,570
Scott: Yeah, I don't know.

935
01:01:39,710 --> 01:01:43,950
Scott: But yeah, I guess there's, you know, the last thing I guess would be the other arrangements of fridges, right?

936
01:01:44,030 --> 01:01:58,110
Rym: A lot of people seem to have strong opinions about, like, the doors, whether you should get the splitting doors or Well, my only preference is there is anything where there's a divider between the two left and right side of the fridge seems just a complete waste of space.

937
01:01:59,030 --> 01:02:04,284
Scott: Yeah, mine has the top doors split in the middle, but the inside of the fridge is one cavern.

938
01:02:04,324 --> 01:02:06,590
Scott: It's notthere's no split in the fridge.

939
01:02:06,970 --> 01:02:08,034
Rym: Yeah.

940
01:02:08,074 --> 01:02:12,370
Rym: I like just one big cavern, and then a smaller one big cavern for the freezer.

941
01:02:14,692 --> 01:02:21,050
Scott: Yeah, I mean, I really don't care too much about thepeople have such strong opinions, like, I don't care about the doors, right?

942
01:02:21,110 --> 01:02:33,090
Scott: I care about the efficiency, and I care about how much space is inside to store food as long as it's enough for the food I have, and I care that it fits in the kitchen and, you know, fits nicely and doesn't stick out too far.

943
01:02:33,090 --> 01:02:41,330
Rym: Which again, living in an apartment, like, one minor annoyance of our fridge, you know, our apartment's big, but it's still It doesn't swing out and hit things or block the way or, you know.

944
01:02:41,611 --> 01:02:50,070
Rym: There is no way to remove the left bottom crisper drawer from our fridge without removing the entire refrigerator door.

945
01:02:51,490 --> 01:02:56,170
Rym: Because you cannot open the fridge door all the way around because it's up against the wall.

946
01:02:58,371 --> 01:03:05,230
Rym: And that's just an annoyance, there's literally no way around that, and that is not a concern for pretty much anyone who lives in a house, but if you live in an apartment

