01:03:05,310 --> 01:03:11,170
Scott: That is a chore I do, like, once a year, is take all the things out of the fridge and clean them, all the shelves and the drawers and everything.

948
01:03:11,210 --> 01:03:19,330
Rym: That one shelf, what I do is, when it's time to clean it Yep, I open the fridge door, and then I clean it as fast as possible.

949
01:03:20,973 --> 01:03:22,390
Rym: Like, I'm in and out of there so quick.

950
01:03:23,371 --> 01:03:23,572
Scott: Yep.

951
01:03:24,255 --> 01:03:27,350
Scott: It is nice to have a rearrangeable shelf, you know, and such and such.

952
01:03:27,656 --> 01:03:27,744
Rym: Yep.

953
01:03:29,230 --> 01:03:36,370
Scott: Oh, the one other feature that our current fridge has that actually I do like is that if you accidentally leave the door open, it'll start beeping at you.

954
01:03:36,550 --> 01:03:36,614
Scott: Ooh.

955
01:03:36,910 --> 01:03:42,590
Scott: It would have been a great help earlier in life, but our fridges did not do that when I was young.

956
01:03:42,610 --> 01:03:50,430
Rym: So once, one time, I think I talked about this in GeekNights, we lost everything in the fridge because the door, like, a pressure thing happened, and the door popped open a tiny bit.

957
01:03:51,091 --> 01:03:53,390
Rym: There was this, it was opened by, I think, the tiniest bit.

958
01:03:54,230 --> 01:03:59,670
Rym: And actually, a lot of the fridge, especially the lower part, still stayed, like, pretty cold.

959
01:04:00,310 --> 01:04:05,269
Rym: But it was just open wide enough to where the light bulb in there turned on.

960
01:04:05,630 --> 01:04:15,190
Rym: And that light bulb was an incandescent bulb pumping out 20 to 40 watts of heat, and it basically cooked everything in the top of the fridge.

961
01:04:16,190 --> 01:04:17,030
Rym: So I had to throw out everything.

962
01:04:17,450 --> 01:04:22,050
Rym: Had it not been an incandescent bulb, we probably would have lost almost nothing in that incident.

963
01:04:22,130 --> 01:04:32,228
Rym: So I did replace both bulbs in our fridge with fridge-safe, cold-temperature-rated LEDs, and they output basically zero heat.

964
01:04:32,429 --> 01:04:33,130
Rym: Like, it's kind of amazing.

965
01:04:33,311 --> 01:04:39,510
Scott: My previous fridge, my previous apartment, I replaced the bulbs, but in this current fridge, I just have whatever it came with.

966
01:04:39,630 --> 01:04:43,528
Scott: I don't even know, I guess if they die, yeah, I'm gonna replace them with the best possible LED.

967
01:04:44,330 --> 01:04:46,890
Rym: Does he gotta get an LED that's designed for fridges?

968
01:04:47,671 --> 01:04:50,290
Scott: Oh yeah, obviously you always put a fridge-specific bulb in there.

969
01:04:50,770 --> 01:04:50,839
Scott: Yup.

970
01:04:52,330 --> 01:04:54,322
Rym: But, uh, yeah, refrigeration.

971
01:04:54,442 --> 01:04:55,670
Rym: Super important to humans.

972
01:04:56,890 --> 01:05:00,429
Rym: I camp and hike, I like camping and hiking and all that stuff.

973
01:05:00,931 --> 01:05:02,869
Rym: And, uh, can't just bring a fridge with you.

974
01:05:05,191 --> 01:05:09,450
Scott: I guess the last thing is that, you know, a lot of other features have been added to fridges these days.

975
01:05:09,670 --> 01:05:18,210
Scott: They're trying to, you know, like, they get some fucking computers in there, and like, things to tell you how much food is left, or, you know, do some smart fridge bullshit.

976
01:05:19,031 --> 01:05:20,850
Scott: All that stuff sucks, get that shit out of here.

977
01:05:21,010 --> 01:05:21,085
Scott: Yup.

978
01:05:21,210 --> 01:05:23,010
Scott: Do not connect your refrigerator to the internet.

979
01:05:23,914 --> 01:05:25,321
Scott: I don't want a fridge with a screen on it.

980
01:05:25,441 --> 01:05:27,350
Scott: No, I don't want none of that shit, get that out of here.

981
01:05:27,630 --> 01:05:37,050
Rym: Yup, unless the fridge were smart enough to, on its own, without me having to do anything, know an inventory of everything that's in it, and provide that to me via an open format.

982
01:05:37,310 --> 01:05:39,449
Scott: That's what they say they can do, but, uh, no.

983
01:05:40,290 --> 01:05:46,930
Rym: Yup, call me when they do that without me having to configure anything, and without me having to connect it to the internet.

